  "books": [
    {
      "bookId": "GEN",
      "testament": "",
      "order": 0,
      "title": "Genesis",
      "abbreviation": "GEN",
      "chapters": [
        {
          "chapter": 8,
          "entries": [
            {
              "rowId": 1,
              "keyParts": [
                "label"
              ],
              "value": "8"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 2,
              "keyParts": [
                2,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v1",
                "label"
              ],
              "value": "1"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 3,
              "keyParts": [
                3,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v1",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "But God remembered"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 4,
              "keyParts": [
                4,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v1",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn The Hebrew word translated “remembered” often carries the sense of acting in accordance with what is remembered, i.e., fulfilling covenant promises (see B. S. Childs, Memory and Tradition in Israel [SBT], especially p. 34)."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 5,
              "keyParts": [
                5,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v1",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "Noah and all the wild animals and domestic animals that were with him in the ark. God caused a wind to blow over"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 6,
              "keyParts": [
                6,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v1",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn Heb “to pass over.”"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 7,
              "keyParts": [
                7,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v1",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "the earth and the waters receded."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 8,
              "keyParts": [
                "v001_NET_GEN_008",
                8,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v1",
                "plain_text"
              ],
              "value": "1 But God remembered Noah and all the wild animals and domestic animals that were with him in the ark. God caused a wind to blow over the earth and the waters receded."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 9,
              "keyParts": [
                9,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v2",
                "label"
              ],
              "value": "2"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 10,
              "keyParts": [
                10,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v2",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "The fountains of the deep and the floodgates of heaven were closed,"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 11,
              "keyParts": [
                11,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v2",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn Some (e.g., NIV) translate the preterite verb forms in this verse as past perfects (e.g., “had been closed”), for it seems likely that the sources of the water would have stopped before the waters receded."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 12,
              "keyParts": [
                12,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v2",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "and the rain stopped falling from the sky."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 13,
              "keyParts": [
                "v002_NET_GEN_008",
                13,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v2",
                "plain_text"
              ],
              "value": "2 The fountains of the deep and the floodgates of heaven were closed, and the rain stopped falling from the sky."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 14,
              "keyParts": [
                14,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v3",
                "label"
              ],
              "value": "3"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 15,
              "keyParts": [
                15,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v3",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "The waters kept receding steadily"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 16,
              "keyParts": [
                16,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v3",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn The construction combines a Qal preterite from שׁוּב (shuv) with its infinitive absolute to indicate continuous action. The infinitive absolute from הָלָךְ (halakh) is included for emphasis: “the waters returned…going and returning.”"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 17,
              "keyParts": [
                17,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v3",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "from the earth, so that they"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 18,
              "keyParts": [
                18,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v3",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn Heb “the waters.” The pronoun (“they”) has been employed in the translation for stylistic reasons."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 19,
              "keyParts": [
                19,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v3",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "had gone down"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 20,
              "keyParts": [
                20,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v3",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn The vav (ו) consecutive with the preterite here describes the consequence of the preceding action."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 21,
              "keyParts": [
                21,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v3",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "by the end of the 150 days."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 22,
              "keyParts": [
                "v003_NET_GEN_008",
                22,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v3",
                "plain_text"
              ],
              "value": "3 The waters kept receding steadily from the earth, so that they had gone down by the end of the 150 days."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 23,
              "keyParts": [
                23,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v4",
                "label"
              ],
              "value": "4"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 24,
              "keyParts": [
                24,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v4",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "On the seventeenth day of the seventh month, the ark came to rest on one of the mountains of Ararat."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 25,
              "keyParts": [
                25,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v4",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn Heb “on the mountains of Ararat.” Obviously a boat (even one as large as the ark) cannot rest on multiple mountains. Perhaps (1) the preposition should be translated “among,” or (2) the plural “mountains” should be understood in the sense of “mountain range” (see E. A. Speiser, Genesis [AB], 53). A more probable option (3) is that the plural indicates an indefinite singular, translated “one of the mountains” (see GKC 400 §124.o).\nsn Ararat is the Hebrew name for Urartu, the name of a mountainous region located north of Mesopotamia in modern day eastern Turkey. See E. M. Yamauchi, Foes from the Northern Frontier (SBA), 29-32; G. J. Wenham, Genesis (WBC), 1:184-85; C. Westermann, Genesis, 1:443-44."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 26,
              "keyParts": [
                "v004_NET_GEN_008",
                26,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v4",
                "plain_text"
              ],
              "value": "4 On the seventeenth day of the seventh month, the ark came to rest on one of the mountains of Ararat."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 27,
              "keyParts": [
                27,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v5",
                "label"
              ],
              "value": "5"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 28,
              "keyParts": [
                28,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v5",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "The waters kept on receding"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 29,
              "keyParts": [
                29,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v5",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn Heb “the waters were going and lessening.” The perfect verb form הָיָה (hayah) is used as an auxiliary verb with the infinitive absolute חָסוֹר (khasor, “lessening”), while the infinitive absolute הָלוֹךְ (halokh) indicates continuous action."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 30,
              "keyParts": [
                30,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v5",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "until the tenth month. On the first day of the tenth month, the tops of the mountains became visible."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 31,
              "keyParts": [
                31,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v5",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn Or “could be seen.”"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 32,
              "keyParts": [
                "v005_NET_GEN_008",
                32,
                "p1",
                "verse",
                "v5",
                "plain_text"
              ],
              "value": "5 The waters kept on receding until the tenth month. On the first day of the tenth month, the tops of the mountains became visible."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 33,
              "keyParts": [
                33,
                "p2",
                "verse",
                "v6",
                "label"
              ],
              "value": "6"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 34,
              "keyParts": [
                34,
                "p2",
                "verse",
                "v6",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "At the end of forty days,"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 35,
              "keyParts": [
                35,
                "p2",
                "verse",
                "v6",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn The introductory verbal form וַיְהִי (vayÿhi), traditionally rendered “and it came to pass,” serves as a temporal indicator and has not been translated here."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 36,
              "keyParts": [
                36,
                "p2",
                "verse",
                "v6",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "Noah opened the window he had made in the ark"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 37,
              "keyParts": [
                37,
                "p2",
                "verse",
                "v6",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn Heb “opened the window in the ark which he had made.” The perfect tense (“had made”) refers to action preceding the opening of the window, and is therefore rendered as a past perfect. Since in English “had made” could refer to either the ark or the window, the order of the phrases was reversed in the translation to clarify that the window is the referent."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 38,
              "keyParts": [
                "v006_NET_GEN_008",
                38,
                "p2",
                "verse",
                "v6",
                "plain_text"
              ],
              "value": "6 At the end of forty days, Noah opened the window he had made in the ark"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 39,
              "keyParts": [
                39,
                "p2",
                "verse",
                "v7",
                "label"
              ],
              "value": "7"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 40,
              "keyParts": [
                40,
                "p2",
                "verse",
                "v7",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "and sent out a raven; it kept flying"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 41,
              "keyParts": [
                41,
                "p2",
                "verse",
                "v7",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn Heb “and it went out, going out and returning.” The Hebrew verb יָצָא (yatsa’), translated here “flying,” is modified by two infinitives absolute indicating that the raven went back and forth."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 42,
              "keyParts": [
                42,
                "p2",
                "verse",
                "v7",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "back and forth until the waters had dried up on the earth."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 43,
              "keyParts": [
                "v007_NET_GEN_008",
                43,
                "p2",
                "verse",
                "v7",
                "plain_text"
              ],
              "value": "7 and sent out a raven; it kept flying back and forth until the waters had dried up on the earth."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 44,
              "keyParts": [
                44,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v8",
                "label"
              ],
              "value": "8"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 45,
              "keyParts": [
                45,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v8",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "Then Noah"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 46,
              "keyParts": [
                46,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v8",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn Heb “he”; the referent (Noah) has been specified in the translation for clarity."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 47,
              "keyParts": [
                47,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v8",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "sent out a dove"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 48,
              "keyParts": [
                48,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v8",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn The Hebrew text adds “from him.” This has not been translated for stylistic reasons, because it is redundant in English."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 49,
              "keyParts": [
                49,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v8",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "to see if the waters had receded"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 50,
              "keyParts": [
                50,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v8",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn The Hebrew verb קָלָל (qalal) normally means “to be light, to be slight”; it refers here to the waters receding."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 51,
              "keyParts": [
                51,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v8",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "from the surface of the ground."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 52,
              "keyParts": [
                "v008_NET_GEN_008",
                52,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v8",
                "plain_text"
              ],
              "value": "8 Then Noah sent out a dove to see if the waters had receded from the surface of the ground."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 53,
              "keyParts": [
                53,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v9",
                "label"
              ],
              "value": "9"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 54,
              "keyParts": [
                54,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v9",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "The dove could not find a resting place for its feet because water still covered"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 55,
              "keyParts": [
                55,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v9",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn The words “still covered” is supplied in the translation for stylistic reasons."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 56,
              "keyParts": [
                56,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v9",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "the surface of the entire earth, and so it returned to Noah"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 57,
              "keyParts": [
                57,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v9",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn Heb “him”; the referent (Noah) has been specified in the translation for clarity."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 58,
              "keyParts": [
                58,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v9",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "in the ark. He stretched out his hand, took the dove,"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 59,
              "keyParts": [
                59,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v9",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn Heb “it”; the referent (the dove) has been specified in the translation for clarity."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 60,
              "keyParts": [
                60,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v9",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "and brought it back into the ark."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 61,
              "keyParts": [
                61,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v9",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn Heb “and he brought it to himself to the ark.”"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 62,
              "keyParts": [
                "v009_NET_GEN_008",
                62,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v9",
                "plain_text"
              ],
              "value": "9 The dove could not find a resting place for its feet because water still covered the surface of the entire earth, and so it returned to Noah in the ark. He stretched out his hand, took the dove, and brought it back into the ark."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 63,
              "keyParts": [
                63,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v10",
                "label"
              ],
              "value": "10"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 64,
              "keyParts": [
                64,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v10",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "He waited seven more days and then sent out the dove again from the ark."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 65,
              "keyParts": [
                "v010_NET_GEN_008",
                65,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v10",
                "plain_text"
              ],
              "value": "10 He waited seven more days and then sent out the dove again from the ark."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 66,
              "keyParts": [
                66,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v11",
                "label"
              ],
              "value": "11"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 67,
              "keyParts": [
                67,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v11",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "When"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 68,
              "keyParts": [
                68,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v11",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn The clause introduced by vav (ו) consecutive is translated as a temporal clause subordinated to the following clause."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 69,
              "keyParts": [
                69,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v11",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "the dove returned to him in the evening, there was"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 70,
              "keyParts": [
                70,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v11",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn The deictic particle הִנֵּה (hinneh) draws attention to the olive leaf. It invites readers to enter into the story, as it were, and look at the olive leaf with their own eyes."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 71,
              "keyParts": [
                71,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v11",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "a freshly plucked olive leaf in its beak! Noah knew that the waters had receded from the earth."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 72,
              "keyParts": [
                "v011_NET_GEN_008",
                72,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v11",
                "plain_text"
              ],
              "value": "11 When the dove returned to him in the evening, there was a freshly plucked olive leaf in its beak! Noah knew that the waters had receded from the earth."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 73,
              "keyParts": [
                73,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v12",
                "label"
              ],
              "value": "12"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 74,
              "keyParts": [
                74,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v12",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "He waited another seven days and sent the dove out again,"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 75,
              "keyParts": [
                75,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v12",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn The word “again” is not in the Hebrew text, but is supplied in the translation for stylistic reasons."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 76,
              "keyParts": [
                76,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v12",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "but it did not return to him this time."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 77,
              "keyParts": [
                77,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v12",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn Heb “it did not again return to him still.” For a study of this section of the flood narrative, see W. O. E. Oesterley, “The Dove with the Olive Leaf (Gen VIII 8–11),” ExpTim 18 (1906/07): 377-78."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 78,
              "keyParts": [
                "v012_NET_GEN_008",
                78,
                "p3",
                "verse",
                "v12",
                "plain_text"
              ],
              "value": "12 He waited another seven days and sent the dove out again, but it did not return to him this time."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 79,
              "keyParts": [
                79,
                "p4",
                "verse",
                "v13",
                "label"
              ],
              "value": "13"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 80,
              "keyParts": [
                80,
                "p4",
                "verse",
                "v13",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "In Noah’s six hundred and first year,"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 81,
              "keyParts": [
                81,
                "p4",
                "verse",
                "v13",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn Heb In the six hundred and first year.” Since this refers to the six hundred and first year of Noah’s life, the word “Noah’s” has been supplied in the translation for clarity."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 82,
              "keyParts": [
                82,
                "p4",
                "verse",
                "v13",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "in the first day of the first month, the waters had dried up from the earth, and Noah removed the covering from the ark and saw that"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 83,
              "keyParts": [
                83,
                "p4",
                "verse",
                "v13",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn Heb “and saw and look.” As in v. 11, the deictic particle הִנֵּה (hinneh) invites readers to enter into the story, as it were, and look at the dry ground with their own eyes."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 84,
              "keyParts": [
                84,
                "p4",
                "verse",
                "v13",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "the surface of the ground was dry."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 85,
              "keyParts": [
                "v013_NET_GEN_008",
                85,
                "p4",
                "verse",
                "v13",
                "plain_text"
              ],
              "value": "13 In Noah’s six hundred and first year, in the first day of the first month, the waters had dried up from the earth, and Noah removed the covering from the ark and saw that the surface of the ground was dry."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 86,
              "keyParts": [
                86,
                "p4",
                "verse",
                "v14",
                "label"
              ],
              "value": "14"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 87,
